he change that conflicted to be part<br />of THEIR subsystem!<br /><br />See?<br /><br />So by definition, if you get conflicts with something that has come<br />into my tree from somebody else, then it is a cross-subsystem<br />conflict. What file it happens in (and whether you consider it "your"<br />file or not) is entirely irrelevant - because the important part is<br />that two different maintainers worked on the same area. That's the<br />definition of 'cross-subsystem conflict'.<br /><br />In contrast, if you merge two different branches that you yourself<br />maintain, and have conflicts there, that's an "internal" conflict as<br />far as maintenance is concerned. I don't particularly care about those<br />internal conflicts, but you might want to talk to the people you work<br />with if you have lots of them..<br /><br />                      Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
